<Page
    x:Class="MCGIApp.PageGlobalEvangelization"
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
    xmlns:local="using:MCGIApp"
    xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
    xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
    mc:Ignorable="d"
    xmlns:custom="using:MCGIApp.View.CustomControl"
    Background="{ThemeResource ApplicationPageBackgroundThemeBrush}">

    <Page.Transitions>
        <TransitionCollection>
            <NavigationThemeTransition>
                <NavigationThemeTransition.DefaultNavigationTransitionInfo>
                    <ContinuumNavigationTransitionInfo/>
                </NavigationThemeTransition.DefaultNavigationTransitionInfo>
            </NavigationThemeTransition>
        </TransitionCollection>
    </Page.Transitions>


    <Grid x:Name="LayoutRoot" Background="{ThemeResource ApplicationBackgroundColor}" Margin="0">
        <Grid.ChildrenTransitions>
            <TransitionCollection>
                <EntranceThemeTransition/>
            </TransitionCollection>
        </Grid.ChildrenTransitions>
        <Grid.RowDefinitions>
            <RowDefinition Height="Auto"/>
            <RowDefinition Height="*"/>
        </Grid.RowDefinitions>

        <StackPanel Grid.Row="0" Margin="0,0,0,15">
            <custom:ApplicationHeader />
            <TextBlock FontSize="28" Foreground="{ThemeResource ApplicationForegroundColor}"
                       Margin="20,-10,0,0" Text="Global Evangelization" />
        </StackPanel>

        <Hub Grid.Row="1" x:Name="Hub" x:Uid="Hub" Foreground="{ThemeResource ApplicationForegroundColor}">

            <HubSection Name="ItemPageSectionOne">
                <DataTemplate>
                    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
                        <StackPanel>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageHeaderTitle}">Radio</TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            After preaching nightly in the towns of Pampanga, Philippines for more than a decade during the 1970s, Bro. Eli Soriano realized that it would take him many more years just to reach a large part of the country. Back then, radio was a popular medium that can offer the means to carry the voice of Bro. Eli to a wider mileage at a cost cheaper than television.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            So in the last quarter of 1980, the Ang Dating Daan radio program was introduced and aired on DWWA 1260 Khz. Produced with a shoe-string budget, the thirty-minute program had allowed Bro. Eli to discuss short bible study lessons.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Thirty years later, Ang Dating Daan would not only be heard through radio, but seen on television, at MCGI's video streaming websites and via seven satellite carriers transmitting the program and its different translations across the globe.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            However, Ang Dating Daan still continues to be heard over radio, especially for those areas in the Philippines beyond the reach of televisions and computers.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">Radyo Natin</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            MCGI takes advantage of Radyo Natin's 100 stations that can reach more remote locations in the Philippines. Radyo Natin is the biggest radio network in the Philippines. It is found in the FM band where it plays music in the morning. Come 8:30 every evening however, Ang Dating Daan airs until 10 p.m.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">UNTV Radyo La Verdad 1350z</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Ang Dating Daan, the longest-running religious program in the country officially debuted on October 9, 2011 at UNTV Radyo La Verdad 1350 Khz, formerly DZHQ 1350 Khz. Radyo La Verdad or 'Truth Radio' serves as the AM home of UNTV, the Philippines' public service network, where ADD airs daily.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            To view the schedule of the Ang Dating Daan program on radio, please see here.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </ScrollViewer>
                </DataTemplate>
            </HubSection>

            <HubSection Name="ItemPageSectionTwo">
                <DataTemplate>
                    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
                        <StackPanel>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageHeaderTitle}">Television</TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            A radio program since 1980, Ang Dating Daan (The Old Path) started television broadcast in 1984 to keep pace with its growing popularity. The program debuted on IBC 13 with a one-hour time slot. At that time, ADD managed with a production crew of just three people.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Bro. Daniel Razon, who was still in high school at the time, took on the director's chair while Sis. Luz Cruz handled set design, research, and helped Bro. Daniel during the editing process. She also did the makeup for Ang Dating Daan's host: Bro. Eli Soriano.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Over the years, Ang Dating Daan's unique format, where Bro. Eli tackles a wide range of biblical topics, including life, religion, science, and history drew more and more viewership. What stands out today as the program's trademark and main attraction is the question-and-answer segment called Itanong Mo Kay Soriano. During this symposium-like segment, people can ask live questions of faith and hear the Bible's answers from Bro. Eli.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Thanks to television, Ang Dating Daan would become familiar to the masses, and the masses familiar to the program and its host, Bro. Eli. On whichever network ADD went - RJTV 29, PTV 4, SBN 21 - the people followed. ADD's set would be overflowing with people for the chance to ask Bro. Eli live on television.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Now, one of the longest-running religious programs in the country continues to serve people through UNTV, the Philippines' Public Service channel. With Bro. Eli preaching abroad, it is not only Filipinos who can be seen on the ADD program lining up for questions, but people of various colors and backgrounds.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Today, The Old Path is broadcast in more than 70 countries in five languages. MCGI leaders are steadfast in exerting efforts for the program to reach even more people, not just on television, but via the Internet and satellite.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            To view the schedule of Ang Dating Daan (a.k.a. The Old Path, El Camino Antiguo, O Caminho Antigo) by region, please click here.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </ScrollViewer>
                </DataTemplate>
            </HubSection>
            
            <HubSection Name="ItemPageSectionThree">
                <DataTemplate>
                    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
                        <StackPanel>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageHeaderTitle}">Internet</TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            In this Information Age, connecting with the rest of the world is just a few hand gestures or voice commands away. Since the year of the infamous Y2K virus, the number of Internet users have quintupled from 360 million in 2000. The World Wide Web spawned more than two billion users in just over a decade, according to RoyalPingdom.com.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Seeing its huge potential to reach countless people across the planet, MCGI launched its first Church website in 1999 and began offering its 24/7 video streaming capabilities the following year. Two years later, AngDatingDaan.org won both the Most Popular Website and People's Choice Awards in the Philippine Web Awards.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            In the years that followed, MCGI then developed more websites to bring to its many online audiences insightful content, relevant features and more interacivity. As its websites reaped similar awards in the following years, the leadership of MCGI notes that the intention in creating websites however remains not to garner laurels, but to be humble online instruments in spreading God's words to all.
                            </TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Explore the websites developed and produced for our various constituents globally to learn more about the Bible with God's help.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">www.AngDatingDaan.org</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Serving Filipinos worldwide with God's words in Tagalog, this website gives users an accessible platform to view Q and A videos, relive debates, and more about the longest-running religious program in the Philippines, Ang Dating Daan.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">www.TheOldPath.tv</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Watch Ask Bro. Eli, Truth in Focus, The Old Path and Q and A videos in this website. As the online home of MCGI's English programs, TheOldPath.TV also brings relevant information to users interested to learn about the radio and television programming and the show's satellite information. Users may opt to subscribe to the newsletter in order to receive event and other updates from the program.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">www.EliSoriano.com</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Meet the Presiding Minister to MCGI through his official website on the World Wide Web. Know more about the life, works, and achievements of this International Evangelist and host of The Old Path.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">www.OCaminhoAntigo.tv</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            In response to the growing ministry in South America, MCGI launched this live-streaming and video archive online portal in Portuguese, complementing its satellite and cable television broadcasts in the continent.
                            </TextBlock>

                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageSubHeaderTitle}">ElCaminoAntiguo.com</TextBlock>
                            <TextBlock Style="{ThemeResource ItemPageContent}">
                            Bienvenido! MCGI's site for Spanish-speaking countries comes packed with Q and A video archives as well as episodes of El Camino Antiguo.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </ScrollViewer>
                </DataTemplate>
            </HubSection>

